  <Finding ID="LLR--1--1">
    <ItemID>LL-EXPL-1.1.1</ItemID>
    <Severity>Major</Severity>
    <Description>
      The low-level requirement LL-EXPL-1.1.1 constrains how requirements are typed (“no requirement shall be labeled with multiple types such as &quot;NFR / FR&quot;”), but the SRP explicitly defines that the type is carried in a dedicated &lt;Type&gt; tag with allowed values “FR” or “NFR”. LL-EXPL-1.1.1 is therefore a meta-process rule about requirements documentation rather than a system function or property. It does not describe behavior of the robot system and cannot be implemented or tested on the target system.
    </Description>
    <Solution>
      Remove LL-EXPL-1.1.1 from the LLR set or move it into a separate process/documentation guideline outside of the product requirements. If you want a system-level constraint on internal type handling, rephrase it to describe system behavior (e.g., “The requirements management tool shall store each requirement with exactly one type attribute equal to ‘FR’ or ‘NFR’.”) and clearly separate such tooling requirements from the robot’s functional/non-functional requirements.
    </Solution>
  </Finding>

  <Finding ID="LLR--1--2">
    <ItemID>HL-EXPL-1.1</ItemID>
    <Severity>Major</Severity>
    <Description>
      The high-level requirement HL-EXPL-1.1 has type “NFR / FR”, which violates SRP 3.3 where each requirement’s type must be either “FR” or “NFR”. Although LL-EXPL-1.1.1 attempts to “fix” this at the system level, the root cause is the incorrect HLR typing itself. This is a documentation/schema violation at HLR level that is not actually resolved by the LLR set.
    </Description>
    <Solution>
      Correct HL-EXPL-1.1 in the HLR document so that its &lt;Type&gt; value is either “FR” or “NFR”, in line with SRP section 3.3. If HL-EXPL-1.1 is only an example and not an actual system requirement, remove it from the HLR set entirely to avoid ambiguity. Afterwards, LL-EXPL-1.1.1 can be revisited or removed as suggested in finding LLR--1--1.
    </Solution>
  </Finding>

  <Finding ID="LLR--1--3">
    <ItemID>LL-EXPL-1.2.5</ItemID>
    <Severity>Minor</Severity>
    <Description>
      LL-EXPL-1.2.5 requires a high-level state machine with at least the states &quot;Idle&quot;, &quot;Exploring&quot;, &quot;ReturningToStart&quot;, and &quot;SecondRun&quot;, but does not specify the concrete transition conditions or control inputs/outputs in sufficient detail to directly drive architecture design. The phrase “according to exploration completion and run control logic” is vague and does not define what triggers transitions (e.g., operator command, exploration termination conditions, completion of path execution).
    </Description>
    <Solution>
      Refine LL-EXPL-1.2.5 into additional LLRs that explicitly state:
      - The events/conditions that cause transitions between each pair of states (e.g., Idle→Exploring, Exploring→ReturningToStart, ReturningToStart→SecondRun, etc.).
      - Whether transitions are triggered automatically based on exploration completion/time limit or require an external user command.
      - The responsibilities of each state in terms of which other components they coordinate (e.g., path planner, motion control).
      This will make it specific enough for architecture design of the state machine and its interfaces.
    </Solution>
  </Finding>

  <Finding ID="LLR--1--4">
    <ItemID>HL-INTERF-6.1</ItemID>
    <Severity>Minor</Severity>
    <Description>
      HL-INTERF-6.1 requires that “The system shall be able to process sensor data defined in the sensor data interface description”. The current LLR set (LL-INTERF-6.1.x, LL-EXPL-1.3.1, LL-MAP-2.1.2, LL-INTERF-6.1.3, LL-RELIAB-5.2.1, etc.) assumes the existence of a “sensor data interface description” but does not provide any low-level requirement that constrains or models this external interface sufficiently for architecture design. The format, transport, update rates, error handling, and addressing (topic/port IDs, etc.) are all delegated to an external document that is not captured as requirements.
    </Description>
    <Solution>
      Add one or more LLRs under INTERF/6.1 that:
      - Specify the key characteristics of the sensor interface needed for architecture (e.g., data transport mechanism, minimum/maximum update rates, latency bounds, required message fields, and allowable sizes).
      - Define how the system shall behave when sensor messages are missing, delayed, or malformed at the interface boundary (beyond internal &quot;validation&quot;).
      This will allow an architecture designer to define concrete interface components (e.g., communication layer, driver modules) without relying exclusively on an external descriptive document.
    </Solution>
  </Finding>

  <Finding ID="LLR--1--5">
    <ItemID>HL-INTERF-6.2</ItemID>
    <Severity>Minor</Severity>
    <Description>
      HL-INTERF-6.2 requires &quot;The system shall be able to send control commands to actuators with commands specified in motor interface description&quot;. The existing LLRs (LL-INTERF-6.2.1–6.2.4, plus usages in other LLRs) again reference an external “motor interface description” but do not capture sufficient low-level constraints for the output interface itself (e.g., communication protocol, timing guarantees, error handling, acknowledgement or feedback requirements) as requirements. This leaves aspects essential for architecture underspecified.
    </Description>
    <Solution>
      Introduce additional LLRs under INTERF/6.2 that:
      - Specify the required characteristics of the actuator command channel (transport, minimum update rate vs. maximum delay, whether commands are best-effort or acknowledged, precision and range of speed/angle values, etc.).
      - Define how command failures or communication errors are to be detected and handled at the interface boundary.
      These should be worded so an architecture designer can define components and communication patterns without relying solely on an external motor interface description.
    </Solution>
  </Finding>

  <Finding ID="LLR--1--6">
    <ItemID>HL-MAP-2.3</ItemID>
    <Severity>Minor</Severity>
    <Description>
      HL-MAP-2.3 requires “Robot shall complete mapping of the maze within 5 minutes.” The current LLRs (LL-MAP-2.3.1, LL-MAP-2.3.2, and LL-EXPL-1.2.3) implement a hard 5-minute limit and termination behavior, but they do not state any performance requirement or strategy that supports “completion” of mapping within 5 minutes (e.g., map coverage targets, minimum exploration speed, limits on computational load). As written, the system could simply terminate at 5 minutes even with very poor coverage and still technically satisfy the LLRs, which weakens the refinement of the HLR.
    </Description>
    <Solution>
      Add at least one additional LLR under MAP/2.3 (and possibly EXPL/1.2) that links the time limit to a minimal mapping performance, for example:
      - A requirement on minimum exploration velocity or decision frequency under nominal conditions, or
      - A requirement on target coverage (e.g., “shall attempt to maximize coverage and reach a specified coverage threshold before the 5-minute limit when feasible under nominal conditions”).
      Ensure wording remains testable, but explicit enough that “completion within 5 minutes” is meaningfully refined, not just limited by a timeout.
    </Solution>
  </Finding>

  <Finding ID="LLR--1--7">
    <ItemID>HL-EXPL-1.2</ItemID>
    <Severity>Minor</Severity>
    <Description>
      HL-EXPL-1.2 states “Robot shall autonomously explore an unknown maze.” While many LLRs refine behavior and mapping (EXPL, MAP, PLAN, RUN, RELIAB, INTERF), there is no explicit LLR specifying the external interface or trigger by which exploration is started or stopped from the user or supervisor perspective. LL-EXPL-1.2.1 defines &quot;exploration mode that, once activated&quot;, but does not specify how it shall be activated (e.g., user input, remote command, physical button), which is important for architecture design of the control and HMI interfaces.
    </Description>
    <Solution>
      Add at least one LLR that:
      - States how exploration mode is initiated and, if applicable, how it can be aborted by an operator (separately from emergency stop).
      - Defines the interface (logical, not necessarily physical) through which this command is provided (e.g., “The system shall provide a command interface that allows an operator to start and stop exploration mode via ...”).
      This will give architecture design clear external entry points and allow mapping of external components (e.g., UI, remote control) to the system.
    </Solution>
  </Finding>

  <Finding ID="LLR--1--8">
    <ItemID>HL-RELIAB-5.2</ItemID>
    <Severity>Minor</Severity>
    <Description>
      HL-RELIAB-5.2 requires that &quot;The robot shall be able to handle faulty sensor data.&quot; Existing LLRs (LL-RELIAB-5.2.1–5.2.4, LL-RELIAB-5.1.2) cover validation, handling policy, degraded mode, and logging. However, none defines explicit thresholds or conditions for declaring a sensor “persistently faulty”, which is critical for architecture and implementation (state, timers, and detection logic). As-is, &quot;persistently faulty&quot; is ambiguous.
    </Description>
    <Solution>
      Add a clarifying LLR under RELIAB/5.2 that defines criteria for persistent faults in a testable manner, for example:
      - A percentage or count of consecutive faulty packets over a defined time window.
      - Time-based thresholds for how long a sensor can remain in a faulty state before triggering degraded mode.
      This will provide concrete inputs to the architecture (e.g., fault monitor components, timers) and remove ambiguity.
    </Solution>
  </Finding>
</Findings>
