<Requirements version="2" hierarchy="LLR">
  <!-- Exploration behaviour -->

  <Requirement ID="LL-EXPL-1.2.1">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Exploration Mode Activation</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-EXPL-1.2</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall provide an exploration mode that, once activated, shall cause the robot to autonomously navigate the maze without requiring further external commands other than an emergency stop.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-EXPL-1.2.2">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Exploration Coverage Strategy</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-EXPL-1.2</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.1</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.2</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall implement an exploration strategy that shall continually select the next movement target such that unvisited or unknown maze cells are preferentially visited until no reachable unknown cells remain.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-EXPL-1.2.3">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Exploration Termination Condition</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-EXPL-1.2</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.1</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.2</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.3</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall terminate exploration mode when either all reachable cells are classified as free or blocked in the internal maze representation, or when the exploration time limit defined for maze mapping is reached.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-EXPL-1.2.4">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Exploration Motion Command Generation</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-EXPL-1.2</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-INTERF-6.2</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall continuously generate motion commands, including at least forward speed and rotational speed, during exploration mode such that the robot follows the currently selected exploration path while respecting active collision avoidance constraints.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-EXPL-1.2.5">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Exploration State Machine</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-EXPL-1.2</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-RUN-4.1</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-RUN-4.2</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall implement a high-level state machine with at least the states "Idle", "Exploring", "ReturningToStart", and "SecondRun" and shall use this state machine to coordinate activation of exploration, return-to-start, and second-run behaviours.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-EXPL-1.2.6">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>State Machine Transitions</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-EXPL-1.2</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-RUN-4.1</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-RUN-4.2</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.3</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall define the following state transitions in the high-level state machine:
      a) "Idle" shall transition to "Exploring" upon reception of a start-exploration command from the external run control interface.
      b) "Exploring" shall transition to "ReturningToStart" when exploration termination conditions are met according to the maze mapping completion and time limit.
      c) "ReturningToStart" shall transition to "SecondRun" when the robot has reached the recorded start cell and a valid efficient path to the target cell has been computed.
      d) "SecondRun" shall transition to "Idle" when the robot has reached the target cell and stopped.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-EXPL-1.2.7">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>State Responsibilities</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-EXPL-1.2</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-RUN-4.1</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-RUN-4.2</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-RUN-4.3</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall assign the following responsibilities to the high-level states:
      a) In "Idle", the system shall command zero motion and shall not perform exploration, mapping updates beyond localization, or path execution.
      b) In "Exploring", the system shall perform maze exploration and mapping and shall generate motion commands according to the exploration strategy.
      c) In "ReturningToStart", the system shall plan and execute a path from the current cell to the start cell while still updating the map and enforcing collision avoidance.
      d) In "SecondRun", the system shall execute the precomputed efficient path from the start cell to the target cell while enforcing collision avoidance.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-EXPL-1.2.8">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Exploration Control Interface</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-EXPL-1.2</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall provide a run control interface that allows an external operator or supervisor component to issue start and stop exploration commands, where:
      a) A start-exploration command shall cause a transition from "Idle" to "Exploring".
      b) A stop-exploration command shall cause a transition from "Exploring" to "Idle" after the robot has safely stopped.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-EXPL-1.2.9">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Exploration Abort Handling</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-EXPL-1.2</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-RELIAB-5.1</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall, upon receiving an operator stop-exploration command or detecting an unrecoverable fault, abort exploration by commanding a stop, disabling further autonomous motion, and transitioning the high-level state machine to "Idle".
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <!-- Wall detection and avoidance -->

  <Requirement ID="LL-EXPL-1.3.1">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Wall Detection from Sensor Data</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-EXPL-1.3</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-RELIAB-5.1</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-INTERF-6.1</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall process incoming range or proximity sensor data at a fixed update rate not lower than 20 Hz to estimate the presence and distance of walls in all directions covered by the sensors within the maze cell in front of the robot and in its current cell.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-EXPL-1.3.2">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Wall Proximity Thresholds</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-EXPL-1.3</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-RELIAB-5.1</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall configure at least one safety distance threshold for each relevant direction, including front, left, and right, such that any detected wall closer than the corresponding threshold shall be considered an imminent collision risk.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-EXPL-1.3.3">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Real-Time Collision Avoidance Control</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-EXPL-1.3</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-RELIAB-5.1</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-INTERF-6.2</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall, upon detecting a wall within the configured safety distance in the direction of motion, adjust or override the current motion command within one sensor update cycle to prevent the robot from moving closer to the wall.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-EXPL-1.3.4">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Wall-Following Behaviour</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-EXPL-1.2</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-EXPL-1.3</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall optionally support a wall-following behaviour, including at least a left-hand or right-hand rule, that uses wall distance estimates to maintain a desired lateral distance from a wall when exploring narrow corridors.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <!-- Map creation and cell classification -->

  <Requirement ID="LL-MAP-2.1.1">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Maze Coordinate System Definition</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.1</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.2</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall define a discrete maze coordinate system consisting of grid cells, where each cell is identified by integer coordinates (x, y) with a configurable cell size corresponding to the physical maze structure.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-MAP-2.1.2">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Robot Pose Estimation</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.1</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-INTERF-6.1</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall estimate the robot pose as (x, y, heading) in maze coordinates by integrating wheel encoder or odometry data and, if available, inertial measurements, updating this estimate at least at 20 Hz.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-MAP-2.1.3">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Pose to Cell Mapping</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.1</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.2</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall map the current estimated robot pose to a corresponding maze grid cell and update this cell index whenever the robot crosses a cell boundary.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-MAP-2.1.4">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Internal Maze Data Structure</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.1</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.2</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall maintain an internal data structure representing the maze grid, where each cell stores at least its classification state, which shall be one of free, blocked, or unknown, and wall existence flags for its four sides, which shall be north, east, south, and west.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-MAP-2.2.1">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Initial Cell State</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.1</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.2</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall initialize every cell in the internal maze representation with the classification state "unknown" before exploration starts.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-MAP-2.2.2">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Free Cell Classification</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.2</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-EXPL-1.3</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall classify a maze cell as "free" when the robot has occupied that cell and sensor data indicate no blocking walls within the traversable area of that cell.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-MAP-2.2.3">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Blocked Cell Classification</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.2</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-EXPL-1.3</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall classify a maze cell as "blocked" when sensor data indicate that the cell is not traversable due to the presence of walls or obstacles across its entrance or interior.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-MAP-2.2.4">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Unknown Cell Preservation</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.2</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall keep the classification state of a cell as "unknown" until sufficient sensor data have been acquired to classify it as "free" or "blocked".
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-MAP-2.2.5">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Wall Existence Update</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.1</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.2</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-EXPL-1.3</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall update the wall existence flags for the sides of the current and adjacent cells based on processed sensor readings, and shall ensure consistency such that a wall on one side of a cell implies a corresponding wall on the adjacent cell side.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-MAP-2.1.5">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Map Persistence During Run</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.1</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall keep the internal maze representation in memory and accessible to other software components for the entire duration of exploration, return, and second run.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <!-- Time constraint for mapping -->

  <Requirement ID="LL-MAP-2.3.1">
    <Type>NFR</Type>
    <Name>Mapping Time Limit Enforcement</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.3</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-EXPL-1.2</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall enforce a hard time limit of 5 minutes from the start of exploration mode for maze mapping, after which exploration mode shall be terminated and the exploration completion procedure shall be triggered.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-MAP-2.3.2">
    <Type>NFR</Type>
    <Name>Mapping Time Measurement</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.3</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall measure elapsed mapping time using a monotonic clock that is not affected by system time adjustments.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-MAP-2.3.3">
    <Type>NFR</Type>
    <Name>Mapping Coverage Performance</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.3</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-EXPL-1.2</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.1</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.2</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      Under nominal sensor and actuator conditions, the system shall attempt to maximize coverage of reachable maze cells and shall target covering at least 90 percent of the reachable cells within the 5 minute mapping time limit by selecting movement targets and speeds that favor visiting unknown cells.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-MAP-2.3.4">
    <Type>NFR</Type>
    <Name>Minimum Exploration Speed</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.3</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-EXPL-1.2</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      Under nominal sensor and actuator conditions in straight, unobstructed corridors, the system shall command a forward speed that results in an average translational velocity not lower than a configured minimum value, which shall be chosen to support achieving the mapping coverage target within 5 minutes.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <!-- Path planning -->

  <Requirement ID="LL-PLAN-3.1.1">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Path Planning Grid Graph</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-PLAN-3.1</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.1</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.2</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall construct a planning graph from the internal maze representation where each traversable cell is a node and edges exist between adjacent free cells that are not separated by walls.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-PLAN-3.1.2">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Path Planning Invocation</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-PLAN-3.1</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-RUN-4.1</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-RUN-4.3</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall invoke the path planning algorithm to compute a path from the robot&apos;s current cell to a specified target cell, including at least the start cell, the maze exit or goal cell, and the start cell for return.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-PLAN-3.1.3">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Shortest Path Computation</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-PLAN-3.1</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-RUN-4.3</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall use a shortest-path algorithm, including at least Dijkstra or A*, with non-negative edge costs to compute a path that minimizes total path cost, where cost is at least proportional to the number of traversed cells.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-PLAN-3.1.4">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Path Representation</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-PLAN-3.1</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall represent a planned path as an ordered sequence of maze cells or movement segments, including at least the sequence of turns and forward movements required to traverse from start to target.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-PLAN-3.1.5">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Unreachable Target Handling</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-PLAN-3.1</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall detect when no path exists between the start cell and the target cell in the planning graph, and in this case shall report the target as unreachable to the higher-level control logic.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-PLAN-3.1.6">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Path Replanning Capability</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-PLAN-3.1</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.2</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall support re-running the path planning algorithm during operation when the maze map is updated in a way that may yield a shorter or newly available path.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <!-- Return to start -->

  <Requirement ID="LL-RUN-4.1.1">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Start Cell Identification</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RUN-4.1</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.1</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall record the maze cell corresponding to the robot&apos;s initial pose as the start cell at the beginning of exploration.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-RUN-4.1.2">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Return Path Planning</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RUN-4.1</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-PLAN-3.1</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      Upon exploration completion, the system shall compute a path from the robot&apos;s current cell to the recorded start cell using the path planning component.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-RUN-4.1.3">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Return Path Execution</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RUN-4.1</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-RUN-4.3</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-INTERF-6.2</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall command the robot to follow the computed path back to the start cell by generating appropriate actuator commands for each segment while still applying collision avoidance.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <!-- Second run and efficient path execution -->

  <Requirement ID="LL-RUN-4.2.1">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Second Run Initiation</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RUN-4.2</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-RUN-4.3</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      After the robot has returned to the start cell, the system shall initiate a second run mode that uses the final maze map to traverse from the start cell to the target cell.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-RUN-4.2.2">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Target Cell Definition</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RUN-4.2</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-PLAN-3.1</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall allow configuration of the target cell, such as the maze goal cell or finish area, and shall use this cell as the destination for the second run.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-RUN-4.3.1">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Efficient Path Selection</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RUN-4.3</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-PLAN-3.1</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall use the shortest-path algorithm on the final maze map to compute the most efficient path from the start cell to the target cell for the second run, minimizing at least the total number of cell transitions.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-RUN-4.3.2">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Second Run Path Execution</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RUN-4.2</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-RUN-4.3</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-INTERF-6.2</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      During the second run, the system shall command the robot to follow the selected efficient path by issuing time- or distance-parameterized motion commands for each planned movement segment while still enforcing collision avoidance.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-RUN-4.3.3">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Second Run Completion Detection</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RUN-4.2</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-RUN-4.3</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall detect completion of the second run when the robot enters the target cell and stops all forward motion commands.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <!-- Reliability: collision avoidance -->

  <Requirement ID="LL-RELIAB-5.1.1">
    <Type>NFR</Type>
    <Name>Collision-Free Distance Margin</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RELIAB-5.1</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall ensure that, under nominal sensor and actuator conditions, the control logic never commands the robot to move such that the estimated minimum distance to any detected wall becomes less than a configured safety margin greater than zero.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-RELIAB-5.1.2">
    <Type>NFR</Type>
    <Name>Emergency Stop Mechanism</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RELIAB-5.1</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-INTERF-6.2</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall implement an emergency stop mechanism that, upon detecting an imminent collision or inconsistent sensor readings indicating possible collision, shall immediately command zero velocity to the actuators.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <!-- Reliability: fault tolerance -->

  <Requirement ID="LL-RELIAB-5.2.1">
    <Type>NFR</Type>
    <Name>Sensor Data Validation</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RELIAB-5.2</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-INTERF-6.1</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall perform validation on each received sensor data packet, including range checks and consistency checks between redundant sensors when available, and shall mark data that fail validation as faulty.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-RELIAB-5.2.2">
    <Type>NFR</Type>
    <Name>Faulty Data Handling Policy</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RELIAB-5.2</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall ignore or down-weight faulty sensor measurements in mapping and collision avoidance computations and shall fall back to last known valid measurements or conservative assumptions when necessary.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-RELIAB-5.2.3">
    <Type>NFR</Type>
    <Name>Degraded Mode Operation</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RELIAB-5.2</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-EXPL-1.2</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      When a critical sensor is detected as persistently faulty, the system shall switch to a degraded operation mode that restricts robot speed, reduces exploration aggressiveness, or halts exploration according to a predefined policy.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-RELIAB-5.2.4">
    <Type>NFR</Type>
    <Name>Sensor Fault Logging</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RELIAB-5.2</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall log occurrences of detected faulty sensor data with at least a timestamp and sensor identifier for subsequent analysis.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-RELIAB-5.2.5">
    <Type>NFR</Type>
    <Name>Persistent Fault Detection Criteria</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-RELIAB-5.2</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall declare a sensor as persistently faulty when either more than a configured percentage of its messages within a configurable time window are marked as faulty or when a configured number of consecutive messages are marked as faulty, and shall use this condition to trigger degraded mode operation.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <!-- Interfaces: sensor processing -->

  <Requirement ID="LL-INTERF-6.1.1">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Sensor Data Acquisition Interface</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-INTERF-6.1</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall implement an input interface that receives sensor data messages as specified in the sensor data interface description, including at least range, encoder, and optional inertial measurements.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-INTERF-6.1.2">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Sensor Data Timestamping</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-INTERF-6.1</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.1</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall associate each received sensor data message with a timestamp from a monotonic clock and shall use these timestamps for pose estimation and time-based filtering.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-INTERF-6.1.3">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Sensor Data Fusion</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-INTERF-6.1</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-EXPL-1.3</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-MAP-2.1</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall fuse data from multiple sensors according to the sensor data interface description to produce consistent estimates of robot pose and wall distances for use by mapping, planning, and control components.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-INTERF-6.1.4">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Sensor Transport Characteristics</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-INTERF-6.1</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall support a sensor data transport mechanism that delivers sensor messages to the processing components with a maximum end-to-end latency not greater than a configured value and an update rate not lower than the minimum processing rate required by wall detection and localization components.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-INTERF-6.1.5">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Sensor Message Format Constraints</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-INTERF-6.1</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall require that each sensor message contain at least a sensor identifier, timestamp, and payload fields for the configured sensor types, and shall reject messages that do not conform to the expected format or exceed a configured maximum size.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-INTERF-6.1.6">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Sensor Interface Error Handling</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-INTERF-6.1</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-RELIAB-5.2</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall detect missing, delayed, or malformed sensor messages at the sensor interface boundary, shall treat such conditions as faulty data for the purpose of validation and fault tolerance logic, and shall log these events together with the affected sensor identifier and a timestamp.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <!-- Interfaces: actuator control -->

  <Requirement ID="LL-INTERF-6.2.1">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Actuator Command Interface</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-INTERF-6.2</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall implement an output interface that sends motor control commands as specified in the motor interface description, including at least target wheel speeds or linear and angular velocities.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-INTERF-6.2.2">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Control Loop Frequency</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-INTERF-6.2</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-EXPL-1.2</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-EXPL-1.3</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall update actuator commands at a fixed control loop frequency of at least 20 Hz to ensure responsive motion control and collision avoidance.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-INTERF-6.2.3">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Low-Level Motion Primitives</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-INTERF-6.2</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-RUN-4.3</Refines>
    </Relationships>
    <Content>
      The system shall expose low-level motion primitives such as "drive forward for distance", "rotate by angle", and "stop", and shall implement each primitive via appropriate sequences of motor commands according to the motor interface description.
    </Content>
  </Requirement>

  <Requirement ID="LL-INTERF-6.2.4">
    <Type>FR</Type>
    <Name>Actuator Command Safety Limits</Name>
    <Relationships>
      <Refines>HL-INTERF-6.2</Refines>
      <Refines>HL-RELIAB-5.1</Refines>
